    blueprintDirective: "Anchor questions in systems the candidate actually built and operated, not textbook designs. The exercise shapes that separate strong from weak in software are a system-design prompt scoped to their claimed scale, a production-incident walkthrough, a debugging scenario with an evolving symptom, and an architecture-decision autopsy. Strong candidates reveal themselves through trade-off reasoning under real constraints, failure-mode anticipation, and operational ownership; weak ones through framework name-dropping. Use stems like \"Walk me through the worst production incident you owned end to end,\" \"Design the notification pipeline you'd need at 50M users — start with the write path,\" \"Your p99 doubled after a deploy; what do you look at in the first ten minutes,\" \"Tell me about a migration you led and what you did with the long tail,\" and \"Where did you draw the wrong service boundary, and how did you find out.\" Fold in 2025-2026 realities: how they verify AI-generated code, platform-engineering golden paths, OpenTelemetry-grade observability, cloud cost trade-offs, supply-chain security. idealSignal is named systems, real QPS/latency/error-budget numbers, and the specific thing that broke; probeIfWeak demands the exact mechanism — the consistency model chosen, the query plan, the rollback that saved them.",
