    blueprintDirective: "First pin which hardware sub-branch the role is — silicon/VLSI, board-level EE, embedded firmware, mechanical, or consumer NPI — and design inside that lane, never generic \"hardware.\" Anchor every exercise in something the candidate shipped or debugged: bring-up war stories, respin post-mortems, design-under-constraint prompts, and measurement-driven debug scenarios are the canonical shapes. What separates strong from weak in this field is physical intuition with numbers attached, measurement-first debug method, and fluency in cost-schedule-yield trade-offs, so build stems like \"walk me through your last board bring-up — what failed at first power-on?\", \"your ADC gets noisy only when the radio transmits — isolate it\", \"design the power tree for a coin-cell sensor and justify every regulator\", \"a hold violation shows up at the SS corner two weeks before tapeout — what are your options?\", or \"ICT fallout hits 8% during PVT ramp — what do you check first?\". Where the role warrants, pull in current practice: chiplets and advanced packaging, DDR5/PCIe Gen6 signal integrity, USB-C PD, GaN power stages, part-substitution requalification, AI-accelerator power density. idealSignal must cite instruments, units, corners, and BOM or yield numbers; probeIfWeak should demand the actual waveform, the exact rail, the specific part, and proof of root cause rather than a patched symptom.",
