    matchTerms: ["actuarial", "actuary", "bind authority", "catastrophe modeling", "claims adjuster", "claims examiner", "combined ratio", "coverage analysis", "cpcu", "duck creek", "facultative", "fcas", "guidewine", "guidewire", "ibnr", "loss ratio", "loss reserving", "loss triangles", "mga", "p&c", "property and casualty", "rate filing", "reinsurance", "solvency ii", "subrogation", "surplus lines", "treaty reinsurance", "underwriter", "underwriting", "workers compensation"],
    blueprintDirective: "Anchor every question in a file the candidate actually touched: a submission they priced, a claim they adjusted, a treaty they renewed, a reserve review they defended. The competencies that separate strong from weak are risk selection under incomplete information, pricing adequacy versus market pressure, coverage analysis grounded in actual policy language, and reserving discipline when triangles turn adverse. Build scenarios from realistic ingredients — incomplete loss runs, a shock loss distorting three-year experience, a late-notice coverage dispute, adverse development in a mature accident year, a cat-exposed book after a model version change. Use stems like \"Walk me through a risk you declined and what in the submission killed it,\" \"Take me through a claim where coverage was genuinely contestable — what did the form actually say,\" \"Your accident-year triangle shows adverse development — how did you decide whether to strengthen,\" and \"How did you set retention and attachment on your last treaty renewal.\" Weave in 2025-2026 realities: social inflation and nuclear verdicts, secondary perils like SCS and wildfire, AI-assisted submission triage and claims automation, parametric covers, IFRS 17/LDTI. idealSignal names the line of business, the gross-versus-net loss ratio, the attachment point, the declination reason; probeIfWeak demands the specific account, the number in the file, and what the reinsurer or regulator said.",
    voiceDirective: "Talk like someone who has sat in referral meetings: say submission, loss runs, attachment point, retention, cede, accident year, ALAE, tail, hard market — naturally, not as jargon display. When a candidate quotes a loss ratio, instinctively ask whether it is gross or net of reinsurance and accident-year or calendar-year; when they describe a claim, ask how it was reserved and whether a reservation of rights went out. If they misuse terms — confusing deductible with self-insured retention, reserving with pricing, ceding with assuming — restate the term correctly in passing and probe whether the slip is verbal or conceptual. Respect precise policy language: when a candidate paraphrases coverage, ask what the form actually said and which endorsement changed it.",
    evaluationLens: "Domain-authentic strength sounds like a file: a named line of business, gross-versus-net loss ratios, a specific declination with the submission detail that drove it, a reserve strengthening with the accident year and the number attached. Fluent-but-hollow answers recite combined-ratio definitions, invoke \"data-driven underwriting\" without a rate indication, or narrate claims handling with no mention of coverage position or reserving. Flag as red: conflating case reserves with pricing, ignoring reinsurance when discussing net retention, no awareness of rate-filing or solvency constraints, and casualness about fraud referral or SIU thresholds. Frame growth feedback in the field's own terms — file documentation quality, referral discipline, knowing when to escalate to coverage counsel or peer review — and name the exact number or policy provision the answer was missing.",
    deepDiveTopics: ["risk selection & pricing adequacy", "claims coverage analysis", "reserving & loss development", "catastrophe modeling & accumulation", "reinsurance structures & treaty renewal", "fraud detection & SIU referral", "regulatory & solvency frameworks", "AI-assisted underwriting & triage", "market cycle & portfolio steering"],
