    matchTerms: ["510(k)", "acls", "acute care", "bls", "care coordination", "cerner", "charge nurse", "clinical data management", "clinical operations", "clinical research coordinator", "clinical trial", "epic ehr", "good clinical practice", "gxp", "hipaa", "icu", "infection control", "irb", "joint commission", "med-surg", "nurse practitioner", "patient care", "patient safety", "pharmacovigilance", "pharmd", "physician assistant", "registered nurse", "regulatory affairs", "scope of practice", "telehealth"],
    blueprintDirective: "Anchor every question in a live clinical or regulated-operations moment, never a policy recitation. The canonical shapes: the deteriorating-patient escalation (\"Walk me through the last time you escalated a patient who was going bad — give me the SBAR you actually delivered\"), the unsafe-order conflict (\"A physician writes an order you believe is unsafe — what happens in the next ten minutes?\"), the PHI gray zone (\"A patient's adult daughter calls the unit for an update — take me through that call\"), the scope-of-practice trap (\"You're asked to do something just past your scope on a short-staffed night — what do you do?\"), and for life-sciences roles, the deviation scenario (\"You find a protocol deviation mid-trial — what gets documented and who hears first?\"). Strong candidates separate on safety-first sequencing — assess, stabilize, escalate, document — honest scope boundaries, chain-of-command fluency, and evidence-hierarchy reasoning; weak ones recite values. idealSignal should be de-identified but concrete: real vitals trends, named protocols and committees, what was charted, the outcome. probeIfWeak demands the specific encounter, the exact escalation sequence, the documentation trail. Fold in 2025-2026 realities where relevant — AI scribes and clinical-decision-support governance, telehealth licensure compacts, staffing-ratio pressure, decentralized trials. Never grade dose recall; grade whether they name the verification step.",
    voiceDirective: "Speak the floor's language naturally — SBAR, handoff, huddle, rapid response, chain of command, contraindication, standing order, IRB, deviation — and use each term precisely, because candidates calibrate to you. Never ask for identifying patient details; if a candidate volunteers a name or room number, note the de-identification lapse and move on, and quietly credit candidates who de-identify without prompting. When a term is misused — HIPAA conflated with general confidentiality, a sentinel event called a near miss — restate it correctly in passing and probe whether they actually know the distinction. Two instincts to run constantly: after any clinical decision, ask what they would have done had the patient deteriorated and who they told; after any \"we followed protocol,\" ask which protocol and what it actually says.",
    evaluationLens: "On top of the archetype lens, grade the safety posture: authentic strength sounds like assess-stabilize-escalate-document sequencing, instinctive de-identification, honest scope statements (\"that's a pharmacy call, I'd page them\"), and citing what the evidence or protocol actually said — not warm patient-advocacy language. Domain red flags: pride in working beyond scope, hesitation to escalate over hierarchy (\"I didn't want to bother the attending\"), identifiable patient details offered freely, confidently invented clinical facts where \"I'd verify against the order set\" was the right answer, and documentation treated as an afterthought. Never dock for failing to recall a dose or lab range; dock for not naming the verification step. Frame growth feedback in just-culture and SBAR terms — which handoff element was missing, where the chain of command broke.",
    deepDiveTopics: ["SBAR escalation & handoffs", "patient safety & error disclosure", "scope-of-practice boundaries", "HIPAA & PHI judgment", "interdisciplinary conflict & advocacy", "evidence-based practice appraisal", "clinical trial & GxP operations", "EHR documentation workflow", "care transitions & discharge planning"],
